posts.title: Day 2 of posting: Mr President! LOWER THE COST OF DIESEL AT ALL COSTS!
posts.content:
50% of the economy could probably be fixed by simply LOWERING THE COST OF DIESEL TO BELOW THAT OF CURRENT GASOLINE PRICES and even lower. It is easier to produce than gasoline, by far more important to us as a nation, can be produced in multiple ways, including from the ground. If you get the nation moving with lower diesel prices, everything will get cheaper on its own quickly. There will be some people who refuse to go back to previous prices. But they will be replaced by bigger, better, American made companies. Who are able, ON THEIR OWN to prosper, and be founded by this one simple change. Here is a summary of what a difference in diesel could do:

  1. Minimal Impact: From $3.66 down to $3.16

Trucking & Logistics:

Small Savings: Large fleets notice slight weekly fuel-bill reductions, but not enough to drastically alter shipping rates.

Minimal Consumer Effect: Retail prices might see tiny downward pressure, though most households barely notice.

Agriculture & Manufacturing:

Incremental Cost Relief: Slight drop in running machinery or transporting goods; any savings are largely used to maintain stable profits.

Muted Price Adjustments: Minimal price reductions for groceries or other everyday items—if any at all.

Overall:

Inflation: May begin to ease marginally.

Consumer Budgets: Little net change in disposable income.

  1. Growing Relief: From $3.16 down to $2.66

Trucking & Logistics:

Notable Decline in Fuel Costs: Moderately cheaper diesel encourages some carriers to reduce freight charges, adding mild competition among shipping companies.

Last-Mile Deliveries: Small businesses handling local deliveries could pass on slight savings to customers.

Retail & Consumer Spending:

Lower Product Prices: Goods that are transport-intensive (fresh produce, heavier items) may start to show modest price dips.

Budget Flexibility: Consumers save a bit more at the checkout, nudging them to spend extra in other sectors like dining out or entertainment.

Agriculture & Food Supply:

Better Profit Margins: Farmers and distributors can maintain or even lower produce prices, helping stabilize food costs.

Overall:

Consumer Confidence: Rises slowly as shipping and everyday goods become more affordable.

Competitive Landscape: Businesses begin to see a real advantage in cost savings; some pass these on to capture market share.

  1. Substantial Gains: From $2.66 down to $2.16

Major Supply Chain Savings:

Trucking Rates: Freight rates drop more visibly, cutting shipping surcharges.

Warehousing & Distribution: Companies can consider stocking more inventory in various regions without fear of high transport overhead.

Manufacturing & Construction:

Production Efficiencies: Reduced diesel expenses lower the cost of operating heavy machinery and equipment, prompting investment in expansions or new technology.

Public Works & Infrastructure: Cities and states that operate diesel fleets (e.g., road construction crews, public works trucks) might redirect fuel budget savings to road maintenance or new projects.

Consumer Market:

Lower Overall Goods Prices: Electronics, household goods, and groceries all become cheaper to move, aiding in more consistent price stabilization or reductions.

Disposable Income Growth: Savings on necessities can result in more discretionary spending—vacations, dining, and home improvements.

Overall:

Economic Growth: Heightened activity from both businesses reinvesting and consumers spending.

Inflation Control: Reduced transport costs help keep broader inflation in check.

  1. Transformational Gains: From $2.16 down to $1.66

Corporate Logistics & Big Retailers:

Significant Fuel-Bill Decreases: Companies like UPS, FedEx, and Amazon see enough savings to potentially lower shipping fees or offer free/discounted delivery more broadly.

Upgrades & Expansion: Capital once spent on fuel may flow into upgrading fleets, warehouses, or technology.

Small and Mid-Sized Enterprises:

Greater Competitiveness: Regional carriers and local businesses can compete more aggressively on price or service, spurring innovation or expansion.

Hiring & Wage Growth: Freed resources might be directed to workforce incentives, potentially raising wages or increasing staff.

National Economy & Consumer Spending:

Vibrant Retail Market: Lower overhead filters through to shops and groceries, amplifying savings for consumers.

Investment & Growth: Investors may see new opportunities in logistics-heavy industries thanks to improved profit margins.

Overall:

Broader Prosperity: Everyone from farmers to online retailers reaps tangible benefits.

Market Competitiveness: More players can enter shipping or delivery markets due to lower fuel costs, heightening competition and potentially driving further price drops.

  1. Near-Opulence: From $1.66 to $1.50

(Final drop of $0.16 rather than $0.25 to reach exactly $1.50.)

Extraordinary Operational Savings:

All-Time Low Fuel Costs: Trucking and delivery sectors operate at minimal fuel overhead, slashing freight fees across the board.

Consumer Goods at Record Affordability: The combination of eliminated or drastically reduced fuel surcharges plus fierce market competition can push retail prices to new lows.

Nationwide Economic Surge:

Boom in Consumer Spending: With a dramatic cut in fuel-driven costs, households see clear savings at the store; extra money circulates into broader sectors like travel, home improvement, and larger discretionary purchases (cars, appliances, etc.).

Business Flourishing: Companies funnel fuel savings into expansions, new product lines, or capital projects—fueling a cycle of investment and profit.

Public Budgets:

Reallocation of Funds: Lower fueling costs for city and state fleets mean more resources for infrastructure, education, or technology—potentially leading to improved public services.

Taxation Nuances: Governments may explore alternative funding if reliant on fuel tax revenue, but short-term budgets for fleet operations could be flush with savings.

Overall:

Widespread Affordability: The drastic decline in diesel prices permeates nearly every facet of the economy, from shipping rates to final consumer costs, lifting the general standard of living.

Prosperity & Expansion: Businesses of all sizes can thrive on leaner transport costs, while consumers benefit from more spending power—leading to a perception of near-opulence in everyday life.
